WEBVTT

00:01.084 --> 00:03.837
Adult Adam: Growing up, my dad
made all sorts of sounds.

00:03.837 --> 00:04.880
There was the grunt...
[ Grunts ]

00:04.880 --> 00:05.797
...the grumble...
[ Grumbles ]

00:05.797 --> 00:06.548
...the mumble...
[ Mumbles ]

00:06.548 --> 00:07.841
...the "Ah!"...
Ah!

00:07.841 --> 00:08.926
...and, of course,
the "Bup, bup, bup!"

00:08.926 --> 00:09.843
Bup, bup, bup!
[ Groans ]

00:09.843 --> 00:10.928
Aah!
But it was his groan

00:10.928 --> 00:12.262
that really told the story.
Oh!

00:12.262 --> 00:14.223
It was the sound he made
before, during,

00:14.223 --> 00:15.599
and after work.
Ah.

00:15.599 --> 00:17.559
It was clear to anyone
within earshot

00:17.559 --> 00:19.102
he didn't enjoy his job.

00:19.102 --> 00:20.187
Allow me to translate.

00:20.187 --> 00:21.522
Toast?
Hnunh.

00:21.522 --> 00:24.107
This groan meant,
"Every day's the same."

00:24.107 --> 00:25.484
Have a good day,
honey.
Hnunh.

00:25.484 --> 00:27.778
And this one meant,
"Not gonna happen."

00:27.778 --> 00:29.738
He does not have the wind
at his back.

00:29.738 --> 00:31.531
I hope I never have to
work for real.

00:31.531 --> 00:33.700
But my dad did,
at his furniture store,

00:33.700 --> 00:36.870
the Ottoman Empire, every day
for the last 20 years.
[ Groans ]

00:36.870 --> 00:38.205
Good morning,
sunshine.

00:38.205 --> 00:40.541
I bought you a Boston cream,
extra cream.

00:40.541 --> 00:43.001
Hnunh.
Meaning,
"I've already had four."

00:43.001 --> 00:45.629
And after a long day
of sitting, selling furniture,

00:45.629 --> 00:48.090
and hanging with Vic,
it was closing time.

00:48.090 --> 00:49.299
Have a blessed
evening, Mur.

00:49.299 --> 00:50.092
Hnunh.

00:50.092 --> 00:52.511
That one was just a groan.

00:52.511 --> 00:55.013
Yep, for my dad,
work wasn't the best.

00:55.013 --> 00:56.932
At least he joyfully
returned home to his family.

00:56.932 --> 00:59.434
Home.
Nobody bother me.

00:59.434 --> 01:01.812
We're all on the same page,
sweetie, so go relax.

01:01.812 --> 01:03.814
The TV's all yours.
Damn right.

01:03.814 --> 01:06.275
And the final groan could only
mean one thing ‐‐

01:06.275 --> 01:08.986
Hnnnunh.
"At least I have you, TV."

01:08.986 --> 01:10.571
♪ I'm twisted up inside ♪

01:10.571 --> 01:13.991
♪ But nonetheless,
I feel the need to say ♪

01:16.410 --> 01:17.869
♪ I don't know the future ♪

01:17.869 --> 01:21.498
♪ But the past keeps getting
clearer every day ♪

01:21.498 --> 01:23.875
It was April 15th,
1980‐something

01:23.875 --> 01:25.335
and, for us drama kids,

01:25.335 --> 01:27.754
the pinnacle of
our otherwise boring year.

01:27.754 --> 01:30.340
This year's spring musical
will be...

01:30.340 --> 01:31.341
nothing.

01:31.341 --> 01:33.302
So, then,
an actual play?

01:33.302 --> 01:35.512
Finally, a gritty role
I can sink my teeth into.

01:35.512 --> 01:37.055
Like maybe
a working‐class galoot

01:37.055 --> 01:38.307
who came back from the war

01:38.307 --> 01:40.017
with one less finger
and a head full of horrors.

01:40.017 --> 01:42.853
His name is Jimbo,
but people call him Tree.

01:42.853 --> 01:44.771
Again, no one's
calling this guy anything,

01:44.771 --> 01:46.064
because it's not a play.

01:46.064 --> 01:47.399
We're doing nothing.

01:47.399 --> 01:49.234
But the cast wrap party
is historically

01:49.234 --> 01:51.028
where Schernecke
shines romantically.

01:51.028 --> 01:53.530
Get your pity smooches
elsewhere, Matt Schernecke.

01:53.530 --> 01:56.033
We're doing bupkis because
the licensing fees went up.

01:56.033 --> 01:58.493
Balls! The musical is
the one time where theater geeks

01:58.493 --> 02:00.579
get light‐to‐moderate fame
in this school.

02:00.579 --> 02:02.247
Football players
would nod at me.

02:02.247 --> 02:03.957
I was a shape
they recognized.

02:03.957 --> 02:07.169
A cheerleader said, "Oh,
it's you," right to my face.

02:07.169 --> 02:08.462
Like we shared
the same world!

02:08.462 --> 02:09.921
What are we gonna do?

02:09.921 --> 02:12.382
Nothing, unless anybody
has any fully fledged material

02:12.382 --> 02:13.717
lying in a drawer at home.

02:13.717 --> 02:15.177
I got some stuff
in a drawer at home

02:15.177 --> 02:16.178
that makes me
fully fledged.

02:16.178 --> 02:17.512
Out!
Way ahead of ya.

02:17.512 --> 02:19.806
Actually,
I have a musical.
Do tell.

02:19.806 --> 02:21.558
It's called
"The Play Ground,"

02:21.558 --> 02:24.811
and it's a meditation
on what it means to play.

02:24.811 --> 02:26.021
Adam made me read it.

02:26.021 --> 02:27.522
It's about a flower
who wants to get planted

02:27.522 --> 02:28.899
on the other side
of a playground.

02:28.899 --> 02:29.941
It's okay.

02:29.941 --> 02:31.693
Okay?!

02:31.693 --> 02:33.528
It might be the best thing
a 12‐year‐old's ever written.

02:33.528 --> 02:35.155
It just needs a finale.

02:35.155 --> 02:36.406
Sounds amateurish
and unfinished,

02:36.406 --> 02:37.699
but it's all we got.

02:37.699 --> 02:39.660
I'm humbled to share
my creative vision with you.

02:39.660 --> 02:40.869
Relax, Tennessee Williams.

02:40.869 --> 02:42.412
Just shove it
in your backpack tonight.

02:42.412 --> 02:44.623
I had no idea
you had a musical in you.

02:44.623 --> 02:47.459
Yep. "The Play Ground"
is an originally penned piece

02:47.459 --> 02:48.752
by me and Erica.

02:48.752 --> 02:50.420
Your older sister
who left for college

02:50.420 --> 02:51.588
and barely acknowledges
your existence?

02:51.588 --> 02:53.256
The very one.

02:53.256 --> 02:55.300
And the minute I tell her we're
putting this production on,

02:55.300 --> 02:57.302
she's gonna be psyched
to dive back in.

02:57.302 --> 02:58.553
God, no!

02:58.553 --> 03:00.681
But it's a chance to see
our work up there in lights!

03:00.681 --> 03:02.057
You have a marquee?

03:02.057 --> 03:04.101
There's a bulletin board
with pins. It's the same.

03:04.101 --> 03:06.311
I had fun writing that with you
like five years ago,

03:06.311 --> 03:08.271
but I'm busy with my studies
and my boyfriend

03:08.271 --> 03:09.564
and not wanting
to do it at all.

03:09.564 --> 03:10.774
Yoo‐hoo.
Geoffy's home.

03:10.774 --> 03:12.317
Oh, my, a guest?

03:12.317 --> 03:14.069
Erica, you didn't say
anything about company.

03:14.069 --> 03:16.446
I'm so sorry. This is not
how it normally looks.

03:16.446 --> 03:18.073
Geoff, stop. You do not
have to clean up for him.

03:18.073 --> 03:19.449
He was just leaving.

03:19.449 --> 03:21.618
So soon? A‐At least
stay for a beverage.

03:21.618 --> 03:22.911
We have Tab
and sink water.

03:22.911 --> 03:24.496
You've tempted me.

03:24.496 --> 03:26.123
I'm gonna park myself right here
and make a night of it.

03:26.123 --> 03:27.666
No!
I have things to do.

03:27.666 --> 03:29.793
Like finish a musical
with your baby brother?

03:29.793 --> 03:32.671
Wow. You guys are a regular
Rodgers and Hammerstein,

03:32.671 --> 03:34.714
except you're siblings
and children and ‐‐

03:34.714 --> 03:36.758
Hey, look, a whole song
about slides!

03:36.758 --> 03:39.553
It's called "The Play Ground,"
and it's set in a playground.

03:39.553 --> 03:40.554
It makes you think.

03:40.554 --> 03:42.139
It almost does.

03:43.432 --> 03:45.851
A duet about monkey bars?
I can't wait.

03:45.851 --> 03:47.811
Well, you're gonna have to,
because it's not happening.

03:47.811 --> 03:50.063
Unless you take my hand
and come with me

03:50.063 --> 03:51.690
to complete
our theatrical destiny.

03:51.690 --> 03:54.359
Ohh! Ow! Ow! Ow! Ow!

03:54.359 --> 03:56.611
Stop by anytime. You're always
welcome in our home.

03:56.611 --> 03:57.863
No, he's not.

03:57.863 --> 03:59.489
And stop offering my Tabs
to people.

03:59.489 --> 04:01.283
While my sister
was kicking me out,

04:01.283 --> 04:03.827
my dad was kicking back
at the office,

04:03.827 --> 04:07.456
until this guy moseyed in ‐‐
Formica Mike, the Formica King,

04:07.456 --> 04:09.875
my dad's local
furniture‐shop rival.

04:09.875 --> 04:12.627
He was gaudy, tacky,
and my dad couldn't stand him.

04:12.627 --> 04:13.920
Hello, Murray Goldberg.

04:13.920 --> 04:15.422
What do you want?
It's not what I want.

04:15.422 --> 04:18.133
It's what I'm offering ‐‐
an invitation to break bread.

04:18.133 --> 04:19.593
I'll break a stale loaf
over your head.

04:19.593 --> 04:20.677
Vic, come on.

04:20.677 --> 04:22.512
I'm sorry,
but I will not fall victim

04:22.512 --> 04:23.972
to this man's
shenanigans.

04:23.972 --> 04:25.599
Have you seen
his commercials?

04:25.599 --> 04:27.559
I can't trust a man who dresses
like a mattress.

04:27.559 --> 04:28.643
Oh, you saw my spots?

04:28.643 --> 04:30.187
Listen,
does it look weird

04:30.187 --> 04:32.147
when that couple's
lying on top of me?

04:32.147 --> 04:34.191
No. Narratively,
it worked fine.

04:34.191 --> 04:36.151
I'm responding
to the costume.

04:36.151 --> 04:37.778
What are we
talking about here?

04:37.778 --> 04:39.696
We're talking about
you, me, and our wives
having dinner together.

04:39.696 --> 04:40.781
What do you say?

04:40.781 --> 04:43.492
I say I've never wanted
to do anything less.

04:43.492 --> 04:46.244
Then I don't have any choice but
to purchase these two chairs.

04:46.244 --> 04:47.412
Our sitting chairs?!

04:47.412 --> 04:48.830
Fine.

04:48.830 --> 04:50.874
If it makes this end,
I'll have dinner with you,

04:50.874 --> 04:52.042
but I'm eating quick.

04:52.042 --> 04:53.335
Is there any other way?

04:53.335 --> 04:55.587
We're going
to Le Bec‐Fin.

04:55.587 --> 04:56.630
It's French.

04:56.630 --> 04:58.048
Holy moly!

04:58.048 --> 04:59.925
It's also considered
the best restaurant in America.

04:59.925 --> 05:01.384
Dick Cavett ate there.

05:01.384 --> 05:04.095
Well, so are we,
this Saturday night.

05:04.095 --> 05:05.680
Tell your wife.

05:05.680 --> 05:06.681
She'll have heard of it.

05:06.681 --> 05:08.099
I doubt it.

05:08.099 --> 05:10.519
Le Bec [bleep] Fin?!

05:10.519 --> 05:11.520
Ohh!

05:11.520 --> 05:12.813
What are you
so excited about?

05:12.813 --> 05:15.148
I thought you hated Formica Mike
and his Formica wife.

05:15.148 --> 05:16.942
I do.
They're snooty garbage

05:16.942 --> 05:19.110
that rub their obscene wealth
in our faces.

05:19.110 --> 05:21.530
But Le Bec‐Fin?!
Oh!

05:21.530 --> 05:24.449
They pour you that little bit
of wine for you to taste,

05:24.449 --> 05:27.160
and you taste it and you go,
"Mmm," but you don't know.

05:27.160 --> 05:28.453
Aren't you
at least curious

05:28.453 --> 05:30.580
as to why these people
want to take us out to dinner?

05:30.580 --> 05:31.414
Nope.

05:31.414 --> 05:33.166
Le Bec‐Fin! Oh!

05:33.166 --> 05:35.043
I'm gonna buy
a new dress, hat,

05:35.043 --> 05:37.003
and over‐the‐elbow
opera gloves!

05:37.003 --> 05:39.130
Opera gloves? What's wrong
with these sink gloves?

05:39.130 --> 05:41.258
Damn it, Murray!
Le Bec‐Fin!

05:41.258 --> 05:42.592
[ Sighs ]

05:42.592 --> 05:45.262
I wish my mom were alive
so I could show her I'd made it.

05:45.262 --> 05:47.931
[ Grumbling ]
As my dad was grumbling
about dinner companions,

05:47.931 --> 05:50.100
I was looking for
a new musical partner.

05:50.100 --> 05:51.601
So, what are we
doing, again?

05:51.601 --> 05:54.479
Erica ditched me, and I gotta
finish a rousing musical

05:54.479 --> 05:56.439
that ties six story lines
together

05:56.439 --> 05:58.984
and makes the audience weep
by tomorrow.

05:58.984 --> 06:00.151
Here's what I got so far.

06:00.151 --> 06:03.864
[ Catchy melody plays ]

06:03.864 --> 06:05.240
Are those
the opening bars

06:05.240 --> 06:07.242
to "You Can Call Me Al"
by Paul Simon?

06:07.242 --> 06:08.869
Gah! I knew
it sounded familiar!

06:08.869 --> 06:10.203
What's this play
about, again?

06:10.203 --> 06:11.872
Well, in this scene,
Phil the Flower

06:11.872 --> 06:14.124
learns his friends are
the real soil in his life.

06:14.124 --> 06:15.083
Maybe this
will do the trick.

06:15.083 --> 06:17.669
[ Arpeggio plays ]

06:17.669 --> 06:19.421
Can you make it sound
more like a full orchestra?

06:19.421 --> 06:20.755
I can kind of make
a shimmer sound.

06:20.755 --> 06:22.716
Balls! Why would Erica
screw me like this?

06:22.716 --> 06:24.759
A handful of drama kids
are counting on me.

06:24.759 --> 06:26.595
I'll do it.
No one's asking you.

06:26.595 --> 06:28.805
And what could you possibly
bring to the table?

06:28.805 --> 06:30.765
Oh, I bring everything
to the table ‐‐

06:30.765 --> 06:33.018
chairs, place mats,
napkin rings,

06:33.018 --> 06:35.437
decorative centerpieces,
candles, my elbows.

06:35.437 --> 06:37.272
Stop naming things
that go on a table!

06:37.272 --> 06:38.398
I need music and lyrics.

06:38.398 --> 06:40.108
Done and done.

06:40.108 --> 06:42.110
I'll write you the greatest rap
known to man,

06:42.110 --> 06:44.112
and you can waste it
on your lazy high school play.

06:44.112 --> 06:45.572
Pass!

06:45.572 --> 06:47.240
I don't need you
showing up out of nowhere,

06:47.240 --> 06:48.783
sucking on a treat,

06:48.783 --> 06:51.119
and insinuating yourself
into my life!

06:51.119 --> 06:52.829
You'll be back.
They all come back.

06:52.829 --> 06:54.956
Except for all the ones
who never come back.

06:54.956 --> 06:56.124
You did the right thing.

06:56.124 --> 06:57.834
Your brother is no friend
to music.

06:57.834 --> 06:59.669
Plus, there's nothing
Erica would hate more

06:59.669 --> 07:01.254
than if I let him
ruin our musical.

07:01.254 --> 07:02.088
Hold on!

07:02.088 --> 07:03.256
Don't say "Hold on."

07:03.256 --> 07:04.341
Nothing good ever happens

07:04.341 --> 07:06.301
when people in your family
say "Hold on"!

07:06.301 --> 07:07.802
If I let Barry
ruin our musical,

07:07.802 --> 07:09.638
Erica will have to step in
and fix it.

07:09.638 --> 07:12.349
That's a huge leap, and it
will most certainly backfire.

07:12.349 --> 07:13.808
Not a chance, Dave Kim.

07:13.808 --> 07:16.645
You can go. And please take
your piano guts with you.

07:16.645 --> 07:18.855
Do you know how long it took to
get this thing down the stairs?

07:18.855 --> 07:20.899
You're not a good friend!

07:20.899 --> 07:22.651
[ Arpeggios playing ]

07:22.651 --> 07:24.110
You're in!

07:24.110 --> 07:25.612
Yes!
What are my parameters?

07:25.612 --> 07:26.738
None. Go wild.

07:26.738 --> 07:28.239
Buck wild?
What's the difference?

07:28.239 --> 07:29.616
You know what?
Surprise me.

07:29.616 --> 07:31.951
Good decision.
You just became a millionaire.

07:31.951 --> 07:33.787
I don't see how,
but sure.

07:33.787 --> 07:35.955
While I enlisted Barry's help,

07:35.955 --> 07:38.958
my mom and dad reported for
dinner with the King and Queen.

07:38.958 --> 07:40.460
Le Bec‐Fin!

07:40.460 --> 07:42.128
I can't believe
we're here!

07:42.128 --> 07:43.505
[ Chuckles ]
And in the back room?

07:43.505 --> 07:46.675
Nothing but VIP, baby.
My Franny demands it.

07:46.675 --> 07:48.301
That's enough
out of you, Mikey.

07:48.301 --> 07:50.136
Although I do love
the privacy.

07:50.136 --> 07:51.971
Who wants to sit
with other people?

07:51.971 --> 07:54.516
If you want to be more alone,
I can make that happen.

07:54.516 --> 07:55.767
Oh, Murray, stop it.

07:55.767 --> 07:57.602
Le Bec‐Fin!

07:57.602 --> 08:00.188
That was gibberish
the first 50 times you said it.

08:00.188 --> 08:02.357
Is this place too good
for a basket of bread?

08:02.357 --> 08:04.693
No, but they do have
this divine Melba toast.

08:04.693 --> 08:06.486
Toast?

08:06.486 --> 08:09.114
I put on pants to eat the one
thing I could make at home?

08:09.114 --> 08:10.657
You know what?
I'm with the big guy here.

08:10.657 --> 08:13.410
Give me a hot cross bun,
plate of salty butter.

08:13.410 --> 08:14.619
That's living.

08:14.619 --> 08:16.955
Say, Fran,
I can't help but admire

08:16.955 --> 08:19.207
your beautiful necklace
and earrings.

08:19.207 --> 08:20.959
Are those emeralds?

08:20.959 --> 08:23.378
Rarer.
Green diamonds.

08:23.378 --> 08:25.547
See, I got this guy
in the diamond district,

08:25.547 --> 08:26.840
a disgusting monster.

08:26.840 --> 08:28.174
I'll hook you up.

08:28.174 --> 08:30.009
Yep, nothing but the best
from my Mikey.

08:30.009 --> 08:32.220
You should see
our Margate house.

08:32.220 --> 08:33.847
You have a house
down the shore?

08:33.847 --> 08:35.390
Four houses in
from the boardwalk.

08:35.390 --> 08:38.017
Did you hear that, Murray?
Four houses in!

08:38.017 --> 08:40.437
And I got a lead on a house
two in from the boardwalk.

08:40.437 --> 08:41.354
[ Beverly gasps ]

08:41.354 --> 08:44.441
Meaning ours
could be available soon.

08:44.441 --> 08:45.608
Wink, wink.

08:45.608 --> 08:46.901
She's winking at me.

08:46.901 --> 08:48.486
We own a shore house now.

08:48.486 --> 08:50.530
How did you get that from
her having crap in her eye?

08:50.530 --> 08:52.407
Oh, we're gonna spend
every summer

08:52.407 --> 08:54.701
with our ungrateful children
and then their children.

08:54.701 --> 08:56.661
We are gonna anchor
our family

08:56.661 --> 08:59.330
to the beautiful brown and gray
shores of New Jersey.

08:59.330 --> 09:00.790
That's how it works
with our crappy kids.

09:00.790 --> 09:02.333
Pure crap,
but we love 'em.

09:02.333 --> 09:04.377
Thanks for getting my wife
all worked up,

09:04.377 --> 09:06.171
but I've already got one house
I can't afford.

09:06.171 --> 09:08.173
Well, maybe I can help you
with that.

09:08.173 --> 09:11.676
Murray, I would very much like
to buy your furniture store.

09:11.676 --> 09:13.053
[ Gasps ]
You serious?

09:13.053 --> 09:14.971
As serious
as my heart issues.

09:14.971 --> 09:17.098
Sometimes it beats fast,
sometimes slow,

09:17.098 --> 09:18.850
sometimes not at all.

09:18.850 --> 09:20.810
I can't believe
we're gonna have a shore house!

09:20.810 --> 09:22.437
And there's gonna be
decorative starfish

09:22.437 --> 09:25.273
and, for some reason...
an oar above the door.

09:25.273 --> 09:26.649
Yeah.
Take it easy, Blackbeard.

09:26.649 --> 09:28.234
We don't even know
what the man's offering.

09:28.234 --> 09:30.236
Now...you do.

09:31.946 --> 09:33.281
Is that a period
or a comma?

09:33.281 --> 09:36.743
Comma, baby.
The punctuation of the wealthy.

09:36.743 --> 09:38.036
[ Gasps ]

09:38.036 --> 09:39.913
Holy [bleep]
starfish money!

09:39.913 --> 09:41.247
We're rich!

09:41.247 --> 09:42.874
We're gonna have everything
monogrammed.

09:42.874 --> 09:44.834
I don't like people
knowing my initials.

09:44.834 --> 09:46.503
I'm gonna have to
mull it over.

09:46.503 --> 09:47.587
You take your time.

09:47.587 --> 09:48.671
You got till tomorrow.

09:51.508 --> 09:54.427
Even though taking
Formica Mike's buyout offer

09:54.427 --> 09:55.804
seemed like a no‐brainer,
our dad wasn't so sure.

09:55.804 --> 09:57.847
I'm home!
I don't want to hear it!

09:57.847 --> 09:59.933
Vic?
W‐What are you doing here?

09:59.933 --> 10:02.644
Beverly pulled me into
your ugly domestic squabble.

10:02.644 --> 10:05.563
Murray, you really need to
consider Formica Mike's offer.

10:05.563 --> 10:08.233
Al, you wanna weigh in?
It was your shop first.

10:08.233 --> 10:10.151
You want your legacy
stripped for parts?

10:10.151 --> 10:12.529
For that kind of dough,
strip away!

10:12.529 --> 10:14.614
It's just furniture.
Who cares?

10:14.614 --> 10:15.698
Agreed!

10:15.698 --> 10:18.409
It's mostly wood.
It's not that special.

10:18.409 --> 10:19.536
Look out the window.

10:19.536 --> 10:21.746
It's everywhere ‐‐
tree, tree, little bush.

10:21.746 --> 10:23.414
We could have
all our friends

10:23.414 --> 10:25.083
to our shore house
on July Fourth,

10:25.083 --> 10:26.626
and they would
quietly speculate

10:26.626 --> 10:28.545
about how much
the house cost.

10:28.545 --> 10:29.754
Oh!
[ Chuckles ]

10:29.754 --> 10:31.464
The envy
would eat 'em alive.

10:31.464 --> 10:33.424
I'd certainly be curious
and resentful.

10:33.424 --> 10:35.176
So, that's what
this is about,

10:35.176 --> 10:36.678
you making
your friends jealous?

10:36.678 --> 10:39.764
And you can finally
stop complaining about work.

10:39.764 --> 10:40.682
I don't complain
about work.

10:40.682 --> 10:42.225
It's all you do!

10:42.225 --> 10:44.727
It's your defining
characteristic as a person!

10:44.727 --> 10:47.105
Your negativity
has pulled me down, too.

10:47.105 --> 10:49.524
I've spoken to my pastor
about it.

10:49.524 --> 10:51.401
He'd like you to join us
at our men's picnic.

10:51.401 --> 10:54.237
Mur, come on.
Take the deal.

10:54.237 --> 10:56.281
I'm not taking it
until he apologizes.

10:56.281 --> 10:57.991
Apologizes to you?
For what?

10:57.991 --> 10:59.492
For big‐timing me.

10:59.492 --> 11:01.953
With his handsome
and excessive offer?

11:01.953 --> 11:04.581
Let him big‐time you, Mur.
Who cares?

11:04.581 --> 11:05.540
I care!

11:05.540 --> 11:07.208
No deal.

11:07.208 --> 11:09.002
Well, if all it takes
is an apology

11:09.002 --> 11:11.045
to get me
a family beach house

11:11.045 --> 11:13.256
that gives me generational
control of my children,

11:13.256 --> 11:14.591
then so be it.

11:14.591 --> 11:18.011
That seems misguided
and selfish, but you do you.

11:18.011 --> 11:20.430
How are you gonna get
the Formica King to apologize

11:20.430 --> 11:22.098
for trying to give Murray
a ton of money?

11:22.098 --> 11:23.558
Easy.

11:23.558 --> 11:25.268
I'm not going to him.

11:25.268 --> 11:26.853
Beverly,
I'm so glad you called.

11:26.853 --> 11:29.189
Who was that woman
who answered your phone?

11:29.189 --> 11:30.815
My secretary.

11:30.815 --> 11:32.233
You have a secretary?
For what?

11:32.233 --> 11:34.235
To do all the things
I don't want to,

11:34.235 --> 11:36.571
which is everything besides
shopping and drinking wine.

11:36.571 --> 11:38.198
My God, I want your life.

11:38.198 --> 11:40.950
It's yours. Just get your Murray
to accept my Mikey's offer.

11:40.950 --> 11:43.995
Well, this might sound crazy,
but could you get Mike

11:43.995 --> 11:46.998
to give Murray just a teensy,
itsy‐bitsy apology?

11:46.998 --> 11:48.583
Done.

11:48.583 --> 11:50.585
I thought
that would be harder.

11:50.585 --> 11:53.338
Please. Apologies are
just words. Words mean nothing.

11:53.338 --> 11:55.006
Ah, that's how I feel!

11:55.006 --> 11:56.925
As my mom and Fran
struck a deal,

11:56.925 --> 11:59.969
I had a plan to make my sister
sorry she turned me down.

11:59.969 --> 12:01.346
Adam!
Please come in.

12:01.346 --> 12:02.639
Welcome to our home.

12:02.639 --> 12:04.349
Mwah! Mwah!

12:04.349 --> 12:05.934
Oh, boy,
coming in hot.

12:05.934 --> 12:07.894
And help yourself
to some gourmet snacks

12:07.894 --> 12:09.812
or a variety
of freshly squeezed juices.

12:09.812 --> 12:10.939
Those are my juices!

12:10.939 --> 12:12.273
And why are you here?

12:12.273 --> 12:13.650
Just letting you know
I found someone

12:13.650 --> 12:15.026
to help me
finish the musical.

12:15.026 --> 12:16.736
Oh, esteemed
creative partner!

12:16.736 --> 12:18.112
Barry?

12:18.112 --> 12:19.822
And is that the chalkboard
from our house?

12:19.822 --> 12:21.491
We tied it to the bumper
and drove it here.

12:21.491 --> 12:22.659
It has little wheels.

12:22.659 --> 12:23.826
Dried fruit or nuts?

12:23.826 --> 12:25.536
I'm allergic to both,
but let's do it.

12:25.536 --> 12:26.871
What the hell
is going on?

12:26.871 --> 12:30.041
Welcome to the new and very
improved "The Play Ground,"

12:30.041 --> 12:32.168
featuring Big Tasty!
Mm!

12:32.168 --> 12:33.920
Dummies,
all the chalk came off.

12:33.920 --> 12:35.296
Oh, stupid outside!

12:35.296 --> 12:37.840
Then I'll summarize. It's
no longer about Phil the Flower.

12:37.840 --> 12:39.676
He was weak and gave the wrong
idea about the playground.

12:39.676 --> 12:41.219
What's this idiot
talking about?

12:41.219 --> 12:43.513
This idiot is talking about
injecting our musical

12:43.513 --> 12:45.473
with explosive,
high‐octane energy.

12:45.473 --> 12:47.767
And it gets
even more bonkers!

12:47.767 --> 12:49.269
Tell her who
the main character is.

12:49.269 --> 12:52.647
A giant, ass‐kicking
Tootsie Roll named Clyde.

12:52.647 --> 12:54.232
Why the hell would
a fighting chocolate treat

12:54.232 --> 12:55.400
be on a playground?

12:55.400 --> 12:56.734
He fell out
of a kid's pocket.

12:56.734 --> 12:58.152
Now he's gotta
find his way back,

12:58.152 --> 13:00.154
with the help of Martin Riggs
of Riggs and Murtaugh.

13:00.154 --> 13:02.365
You put the "Lethal Weapon" guys
in your musical?

13:02.365 --> 13:04.242
Just Riggs.
He's an emotional time bomb,

13:04.242 --> 13:05.952
and he's got three
jaunty numbers.

13:05.952 --> 13:07.370
This is clinically insane.

13:07.370 --> 13:09.414
That's the Riggs character.
But don't worry.

13:09.414 --> 13:11.582
He accidentally blows himself up
in the second act.

13:11.582 --> 13:13.209
There's violence
on the playground?!

13:13.209 --> 13:14.377
And tons of sex.

13:14.377 --> 13:16.254
You know that big metal thing
you spin?

13:16.254 --> 13:18.256
Some randy teens
do unspeakable things on it.

13:18.256 --> 13:20.049
And the nudity
is not tasteful.

13:20.049 --> 13:21.467
But isn't this show
for kids?

13:21.467 --> 13:23.219
I don't know who it's for.
I just know it kicks ass.

13:23.219 --> 13:24.762
Now tell 'em about
the big finale.

13:24.762 --> 13:27.557
Clyde the talking Tootsie
defends the playground

13:27.557 --> 13:30.226
by destroying a robotic shark
in a rap battle.

13:30.226 --> 13:31.686
It's a real departure
from the original ‐‐

13:31.686 --> 13:33.229
and also reality.

13:33.229 --> 13:35.315
Enough!
You clearly ruined it!

13:35.315 --> 13:38.651
But I thought you didn't care
about "The Play Ground" anymore.

13:38.651 --> 13:41.487
Not until you completely
ripped out its emotional appeal.

13:41.487 --> 13:43.781
It's about the chutes
and ladders of childhood,

13:43.781 --> 13:45.283
not shark robots.

13:45.283 --> 13:47.201
Robotic sharks.

13:47.201 --> 13:49.078
It's a small
but important distinction.

13:49.078 --> 13:50.872
I guess
there's a solution ‐‐

13:50.872 --> 13:53.041
you come back to finish
what we started.

13:53.041 --> 13:54.459
Damn it, fine!

13:54.459 --> 13:55.793
Sweet!
Barry, you're fired.

13:55.793 --> 13:57.253
You'll regret this.

13:57.253 --> 14:00.256
I don't know how, and you're
my ride, but this isn't over.

14:00.256 --> 14:02.216
[ Sighs ]
I'll be waiting downstairs.

14:02.216 --> 14:03.342
See ya at
the piano tomorrow.

14:03.342 --> 14:04.635
[ Chuckles ]
Ta!

14:04.635 --> 14:06.304
You think everyone
had a nice time?

14:06.304 --> 14:08.848
While my old musical duo
was back in business,

14:08.848 --> 14:12.310
my mom had one last shot to get
my dad to take Mike's deal.

14:12.310 --> 14:14.103
[ Groans ] I can't believe
you dragged me

14:14.103 --> 14:15.772
to this dumb
country club.

14:15.772 --> 14:17.857
Dumb?
It's Ashborn.

14:17.857 --> 14:20.068
I don't care where we are.
I don't want to be here.

14:20.068 --> 14:22.403
When have you ever said no
to a free buffet?

14:22.403 --> 14:25.073
Plus, Formica Mike
is gonna apologize

14:25.073 --> 14:27.200
for whatever minor indignity
you suffered.

14:27.200 --> 14:29.494
I'll believe that
when I see it.

14:29.494 --> 14:30.828
Is that
a carving station?

14:30.828 --> 14:32.163
You bet your tuchus.

14:32.163 --> 14:34.540
Help yourself
to some meaty delights.

14:34.540 --> 14:35.625
How many slices
can I get?

14:35.625 --> 14:36.959
Take the whole
damn tenderloin.

14:36.959 --> 14:39.796
Jimbo, put the sweet beast
onto his plate.

14:39.796 --> 14:40.671
[ Knives scraping ]

14:40.671 --> 14:42.215
I told you
this would work.

14:42.215 --> 14:44.759
Pretty soon I'll be on
the shore, under an umbrella,

14:44.759 --> 14:47.178
yelling at my grandkids not to
play Frisbee with strangers.

14:47.178 --> 14:48.513
That's the dream.

14:48.513 --> 14:50.098
And when you're
finished with that,

14:50.098 --> 14:51.724
head over
to the dessert table,

14:51.724 --> 14:53.851
grab yourself a big chunk
of Black Forest cake.

14:53.851 --> 14:56.395
It's gonna ruin you for
two days, but it's worth it.

14:56.395 --> 14:57.814
Yep, despite my dad

14:57.814 --> 14:59.774
wanting nothing to do
with country‐club life,

14:59.774 --> 15:01.943
he did start to enjoy
the perks.

15:01.943 --> 15:04.445
You found the schvitz.
Thought you disappeared.

15:04.445 --> 15:05.905
I have to admit,
this is nice.

15:05.905 --> 15:07.573
The nicest.

15:07.573 --> 15:09.826
And all this can be yours,
Murray.

15:09.826 --> 15:11.244
Is that your apology?

15:11.244 --> 15:12.328
No.

15:12.328 --> 15:13.830
This is.

15:13.830 --> 15:17.208
I deeply regret my action
of offering you all that money.

15:17.208 --> 15:18.835
Please accept my apology

15:18.835 --> 15:21.420
and all the money that
I originally offered you.

15:21.420 --> 15:24.132
In that moment,
one "yes" from my dad

15:24.132 --> 15:26.050
would change our lives forever.

15:26.050 --> 15:27.385
Instead, this happened.

15:27.385 --> 15:29.554
Bevy, get the car.
We're going.

15:29.554 --> 15:31.180
Where's your pants?!

15:31.180 --> 15:33.599
Stuck in a locker.
I don't know the combination.

15:33.599 --> 15:35.726
You didn't take the deal?
It's what you wanted!

15:35.726 --> 15:37.103
No.
It's what you wanted.

15:37.103 --> 15:39.147
I want to go to work
every day.

15:39.147 --> 15:41.023
What?
You hate going to work!

15:41.023 --> 15:43.693
I know it seems like that,
but I love my job.

15:43.693 --> 15:45.486
But you're never
not complaining about it.

15:45.486 --> 15:47.238
Because I love
complaining.

15:47.238 --> 15:49.240
And I love filling up
the cash register.

15:49.240 --> 15:51.242
And I love
the dumb customers.

15:51.242 --> 15:53.119
And I love having lunch
with Vic.

15:54.704 --> 15:55.830
I love it.

15:55.830 --> 15:57.915
I didn't know that.

15:57.915 --> 15:59.458
Well, now you do.

15:59.458 --> 16:04.630
♪♪

16:04.630 --> 16:05.965
There's my girl.

16:05.965 --> 16:09.218
I got everything we need ‐‐
a piano, a kazoo,

16:09.218 --> 16:12.263
and the finest instrument
there is, these sweet pipes.

16:12.263 --> 16:13.973
Save it, Streisand.
Here ya go.

16:13.973 --> 16:15.725
Whazdis?
The song you wanted.

16:15.725 --> 16:16.934
But we haven't even
written it yet.

16:16.934 --> 16:18.227
I did. Last night.

16:18.227 --> 16:19.770
I figured it was easier
that way.

16:19.770 --> 16:20.771
It's not about easy.

16:20.771 --> 16:21.939
It's about collaborating,

16:21.939 --> 16:23.733
coming together through
the power of music.

16:23.733 --> 16:25.193
Hit the bricks,
Goldturds.

16:25.193 --> 16:26.986
I signed out this room
for band practice.

16:26.986 --> 16:28.279
No, you didn't.
I did.

16:28.279 --> 16:29.864
Oh.
It was worth a shot.

16:29.864 --> 16:31.449
And we're gonna be here
for a while

16:31.449 --> 16:33.701
because we're writing the grand
finale to our musical together.

16:33.701 --> 16:35.077
We're not.
Take the room.

16:35.077 --> 16:36.787
Cool beans.
Not cool beans!

16:36.787 --> 16:38.497
I don't want this.

16:38.497 --> 16:41.167
What the hell, man?!
That took me 20 minutes!

16:41.167 --> 16:43.419
Band drama. Noice.
Been there.

16:43.419 --> 16:46.172
I've been asked to leave
over 243 bands.

16:46.172 --> 16:47.757
Then maybe
you two should jam.

16:47.757 --> 16:49.634
In!
Our name is Butt Oven.

16:49.634 --> 16:52.386
I'm lead vocals and guitar,
and you carry everything.

16:52.386 --> 16:53.930
I'm not joining
Butt Oven!

16:53.930 --> 16:55.765
I wanna write a song
with my sister.

16:55.765 --> 16:57.058
I see why you two
didn't work out.

16:57.058 --> 16:58.226
This one's a diva.

16:58.226 --> 16:59.810
Good stuff.
So I'm gonna hit it.

16:59.810 --> 17:01.312
Don't just go.
Please?

17:01.312 --> 17:03.064
Dude, what is going on
with you?

17:03.064 --> 17:04.232
What's going on with you?

17:04.232 --> 17:05.858
I haven't seen you
all year.

17:05.858 --> 17:07.610
I see you all the time.

17:07.610 --> 17:10.529
When you're doing your laundry
or try to pry money from Dad.

17:10.529 --> 17:13.115
You went to college,
and we became strangers.

17:13.115 --> 17:15.534
So, what, this is your
lame attempt to reconnect?

17:15.534 --> 17:18.454
It was lame,
but it was all I had.

17:18.454 --> 17:20.081
And obviously
it didn't work.

17:21.540 --> 17:23.251
See you whenever.

17:23.251 --> 17:25.544
[ Cassette clatters ]

17:25.544 --> 17:27.046
[ Sighs ]

17:29.298 --> 17:32.426
After my sister rejected me
and I rejected her song,

17:32.426 --> 17:34.428
the musical was stuck with
the biggest reject of all ‐‐

17:34.428 --> 17:35.429
Barry.

17:35.429 --> 17:37.723
This was
a good decision.

17:37.723 --> 17:39.767
I guess, man.
Just do whatever.

17:39.767 --> 17:41.060
Okay, dress is up.

17:41.060 --> 17:43.271
I need my Tootsie Roll
and my Shark‐I‐Tron!

17:43.271 --> 17:45.022
It's always been a dream
to work together.

17:45.022 --> 17:46.524
[ Chuckles ]
What am I, again?

17:46.524 --> 17:48.150
The fool I'm about to
lyrically smoke.

17:48.150 --> 17:49.569
Drop a beat!

17:49.569 --> 17:52.029
You know, I had my doubts, but
I think that this might work.

17:52.029 --> 17:54.490
[ Rapping ]
♪ I'm a Tootsie Roll,
my name is Clyde ♪

17:54.490 --> 17:56.867
♪ On the playground,
I go down the slide ♪

17:56.867 --> 17:59.036
♪ I ride the swings
and the seesaw ♪

17:59.036 --> 18:01.497
♪ With my main man Riggs,
but not Murtaugh ♪

18:01.497 --> 18:03.791
♪ Something's comin'
in the park ♪

18:03.791 --> 18:06.544
♪ It's a giant
monster robot shark ♪

18:06.544 --> 18:08.671
♪ The kids all jump,
the sharks attack ♪

18:08.671 --> 18:11.215
♪ Riggs jumps on
my Tootsie back ♪

18:11.215 --> 18:13.551
♪ That's how I roll,
Clyde the Tootsie ♪

18:13.551 --> 18:16.095
♪ Now all the fly ladies
wanna play footsie ♪

18:16.095 --> 18:18.055
♪ Rest in peace, Martin Riggs! ♪

18:18.055 --> 18:19.640
Why do I keep
believing in children?

18:19.640 --> 18:21.767
Good art is supposed to
make you ask questions.

18:21.767 --> 18:24.353
Here's one ‐‐ how could
half the partnership
from "Lethal Weapon"

18:24.353 --> 18:26.063
be friends with
a piece of candy?

18:26.063 --> 18:27.523
That's your problem
with it?

18:27.523 --> 18:29.775
That's nothing a way‐too‐long
backstory rap can't solve.

18:29.775 --> 18:31.068
Or there's
another option.

18:31.068 --> 18:32.486
Erica?
Why are you here?

18:32.486 --> 18:33.487
To apologize.

18:33.487 --> 18:35.239
Everything you said
was true ‐‐

18:35.239 --> 18:37.408
I've been prioritizing stuff
over you, and it's not cool.

18:38.826 --> 18:41.287
And I don't want it
to be just words. I mean it.

18:41.287 --> 18:43.497
No matter where I'm at
in my life, I want you in it.

18:43.497 --> 18:44.915
You're my baby brother.

18:44.915 --> 18:47.001
So what are you saying?

18:47.001 --> 18:49.253
I'm saying that it's time
for Goldberg and Goldberg

18:49.253 --> 18:50.671
to finish
what they started.

18:52.131 --> 18:53.591
Tootsie Roll, shark boy,
you're out.

18:53.591 --> 18:55.551
Whatever!
I don't need any of you.

18:55.551 --> 18:57.553
Except to get me
out of this thing.

18:57.553 --> 18:58.763
Somebody unzip him!

19:01.307 --> 19:02.892
Hey.

19:02.892 --> 19:04.185
I don't wanna
talk about it.

19:04.185 --> 19:05.895
I do.

19:05.895 --> 19:08.689
All this time, I thought
I knew everything about you,

19:08.689 --> 19:10.191
and I guess I don't.

19:10.191 --> 19:12.443
Well, I certainly
don't make it easy.

19:12.443 --> 19:13.944
Well,
we could both be better

19:13.944 --> 19:15.655
about telling each other
what we want.

19:15.655 --> 19:18.491
I didn't know you wanted
a beach house so badly.

19:18.491 --> 19:21.202
I don't care about
some dumb house.

19:21.202 --> 19:23.204
I care about
what's in it ‐‐

19:23.204 --> 19:27.500
our family being together
and happy.

19:27.500 --> 19:30.086
If I can have all that,
it can always be right here.

19:30.086 --> 19:31.921
But the thing is,
Mike's right.

19:31.921 --> 19:33.547
My business is changing.

19:33.547 --> 19:34.715
So what are you thinking?

19:34.715 --> 19:36.592
I'm not sure.

19:36.592 --> 19:39.512
But I do know
I've been too complacent.

19:39.512 --> 19:41.764
And if we're ever gonna
get that shore house,

19:41.764 --> 19:43.224
I got to do something bold.

19:45.685 --> 19:48.938
Well, whatever you do,
I'm always right behind you.

19:48.938 --> 19:51.357
[ Paul Simon's
"You Can Call Me Al" plays ]

19:51.357 --> 19:53.192
Sometimes it takes a glimpse
of the future

19:53.192 --> 19:54.819
to help you focus on the now.

19:54.819 --> 19:56.195
You wanted to talk?

19:56.195 --> 19:59.240
You want to expand.
I don't want to sell.

19:59.240 --> 20:01.659
So why don't we go
in business together?

20:01.659 --> 20:02.660
Partners?

20:02.660 --> 20:04.870
I figured that you and I
could team up

20:04.870 --> 20:06.122
and take on the big boys.

20:06.122 --> 20:08.207
Or become the big boys.

20:08.207 --> 20:09.875
Life is full of surprises...

20:09.875 --> 20:11.794
♪ ...call me Al ♪

20:11.794 --> 20:15.256
...like when the people from
your past find their way back.

20:15.256 --> 20:17.258
And when you're open
to new possibilities,

20:17.258 --> 20:18.718
the future is bright.
[ Camera shutters clicking ]

20:18.718 --> 20:22.388
I feel like we didn't kick the
tires on the name long enough.

20:22.388 --> 20:25.057
[ Camera shutters clicking ]
Buckle up, Murray.
I'm a difficult partner.

20:25.057 --> 20:28.060
It's true.
He's way too much.

20:28.060 --> 20:31.605
In the end, as long as you make
time for the people you love,

20:31.605 --> 20:34.608
the playground of life
can be a lot more fun.

